{{Shinto Shrine ||name=Kotohira Shrine (Shinkamigotō, Mikano-ura-gō)|native_name=金刀比羅神社 |religious_affiliation={{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft}}|image=[[File:IMG_mika.JPG|250px]] |location=313 Matsugasaki, Mikano-ura, Shinkamigotō, Minamimatsuura District, {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|qq=draft}} |location={{coordinates|32|57|47.2|N|129|03|08.0|E|scale:25000}} |religious_affiliation={{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft}}|deity=Ōmononushi ({{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主命|qq=draft}}) |religious_affiliation={{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft}}|type=Former unranked shrine ({{ill|UnRanked Shrine|ja|無格社|qq=draft}}) |Foundation=Unknown (不詳) |Main sanctuary= |Alias=Matsugasaki Gongen (松ヶ崎権現) |Sacred Sites= |religious_affiliation={{ill|Shinto|ja|神道|qq=draft}}|festival=October 30 (10月30日) |Rituals= }}
'''Kotohira Shrine''' (Kotohira-jinja) is a {{ill|Shrine|ja|神社|qq=draft}} located in {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|ja|長崎県|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Minamimatsuura District|ja|南松浦郡|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Shinkamigotō|ja|新上五島町|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Mikano-ura|ja|三日ノ浦郷|qq=draft}}.
== Deity == It enshrines {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主命|qq=draft}} as its principal deity, and also enshrines two deities, {{ill|Kotoshironushi|ja|事代主命|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kanayamahiko|ja|金山彦命|qq=draft}}, through {{ill|Joint Enshrinement|ja|合祀|1=co-Enshrinement|2=ja|3=合祀|qq=draft}}.
== History == [[File:IMG_mika1.JPG|180px|thumb|Shrine building]] The founding date is unknown. In ancient times, the shrine was known by the name '''Sannō Gongen-sha''', but after either being called '''Mikka Sannō''' or following the joint enshrinement of Kotoshironushi and Kanayamahiko, it came to be known as '''Ebisu Shrine'''. Moreover, as this shrine served as the head shrine for {{ill|Arakawa District|ja|荒川郷|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Yodake Hie Shrine|ja|雄嶽日枝神社|qq=draft}}, and was enshrined on a subsidiary peak to the west of the Arakawa/Sannō mountains, it is presumed that it also enshrined their {{ill|Bunrei|ja|分霊|qq=draft}}.
On May 5, {{ill|1875|ja|1875|qq=draft}} (the 7th year of the {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft}} era), it was classified as an {{ill|UnRanked Shrine|ja|無格社|qq=draft}}, and in the 14th year ({{ill|1882|ja|1882|qq=draft}}) it was renamed '''Kotohira Shrine'''.
== Rites == Although the shrine is located in the former {{ill|Shinkamigotō|ja|上五島町|qq=draft}}, due to the fact that the priests of {{ill|Kagura|ja|神楽|qq=draft}}-less shrines at {{ill|Arakawa District|ja|荒川郷|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Yodake Hie Shrine|ja|雄嶽日枝神社|qq=draft}} are in charge, there is no offering of {{ill|Shinkamigotō Kagura|ja|上五島神楽|qq=draft}}.
; Major Festivals and Rituals * {{ill|Annual Festival|ja|例大祭|qq=draft}} (November 24–25)
{{-}}
== Other Shrines == Among the other shrines in Mikano-ura, there is a '''Yama Shrine'''. In addition, in the adjacent {{ill|Aikawa District|ja|相河郷|qq=draft}} there is a '''{{ill|Hime Shrine|ja|姫神社|qq=draft}}''', and in {{ill|Imazato District|ja|今里郷|qq=draft}} there is a '''{{ill|Ōyamatsumi Shrine|ja|大山祇神社 (新上五島町今里郷)|lt=Ōyamatsumi Shrine|lt_ja=大山祇神社|qq=draft}}'''.
<gallery> File: IMG_aiko.JPG|Hime Shrine (Aikawa District) File: IMG_imazato.JPG|Ōyamatsumi Shrine (Imazato District) </gallery>
== References == *『{{ill|Shinkamigotō|ja|上五島町|qq=draft}} Local History, Heisei 16』 – Shinkamigotō Board of Education *『Exploring the Cultural Heritage of Shinkamigotō』 – Shinkamigotō Board of Education, Heisei 3 *『Goto Shrine Chronicles, Showa 18 (Reprint Edition)』 – Shingi Association, Minamimatsuura District Branch
